<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n58062b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n58" href="#n58062b">N58 (VI.B.30)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n58all.htm#n58062b"> 62(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> because = to use / and = to be / included / and = be parallel / or = partake / if = to permit <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Conjunctions are similarly derivative, they usually serve to mediate actions between verbs, and therefore they are necessarily themselves actions. Thus in Chinese: <mark>Because = to use; and = to be included under one; another form of &ldquo;and&rdquo; = to be parallel; or = to partake; if = to let one do, to permit</mark>. <small> Ernest Fenollosa, &ldquo;The Chinese Written Character as a Medium for Poetry&rdquo;, in <a name="EFCW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EFCW"><cite title="source">Instigations of Ezra Pound</cite></a> (1920) 375</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Transferred to <a name="n58072e" href="n58all.htm#n58072e">N58 (VI.B.30):072(e)</a>, <a name="n58072f" href="n58all.htm#n58072f">N58 (VI.B.30):072(f)</a>, <a name="n58072g" href="n58all.htm#n58072g">N58 (VI.B.30):072(g)</a>, <a name="n58072h" href="n58all.htm#n58072h">N58 (VI.B.30):072(h)</a>, <a name="n58072i" href="n58all.htm#n58072i">N58 (VI.B.30):072(i)</a>.</mm> </dd></dl>
